Finding Patterns in Public GIS Data¶

Overview¶

What?¶

Find out how many patterns can we discover in 20 minutes with public GIS data

How?¶

  • 1) Analyze a handful of quantitative relationships between our datases
  • 2) Then transform those relationships into a spatial relationships

In Python!¶

https://developers.arcgis.com/python/

What data are we using?¶

We need to find patterns between scooter trip counts and other data¶

Let's look for spatial patterns¶

Another possibility: replace counts with relative frequencies¶

  • Calculate the sum of all scooter trip counts: ($N$)
  • Collect all the scooter counts for each intersection $i$: ($s_i$)
  • Divide $s_i$ by $N$ to cacluate the relative frequencies of scooter trips at $i$: $\large s_i/N$, where $\sum s_i = N$

Are scooter trip counts correlated with nearby transit stop counts?¶

Summarize Nearby - Spatial Analysis¶

def calculate_nearby_stops(
    stops_layer, 
    scooter_quantile_layers, 
    near_type='Walking Distance', distances=[20.0], units='Meters'):    

    nearby = OrderedDict()
    for title, layer in scooter_quantile_layers.items():
        kw = { 'sum_nearby_layer': layer, 'summary_layer': stops_layer, 
            'near_type': near_type, 'distances': distances, 'units': units }
        nearby[title] = arcgis.features.analysis.summarize_nearby(**kw)
    return nearby

stops_layer is from static GTFS data

hottest_nearby = calculate_nearby_stops(stops_layer, hottest_scooter_layers)

Easy to combine our nearby transit stop data¶

In [187]:
from functools import reduce
index = ['Hex_X', 'Hex_Y']
columns = ['Point_Count', 'Rounded_Tr', 'Hex_X', 'Hex_Y']
fn = lambda l, r: pandas.concat([l.set_index(index), r.set_index(index)]).reset_index()

nearby_dfs = [nearby_result['result_layer'].query().sdf[columns] for nearby_result in hottest_nearby.values()]
combined_nearby_df = reduce(lambda l,r: fn(l, r), nearby_dfs).sort_values('Rounded_Tr')
combined_nearby_sdf = arcgis.features.GeoAccessor.from_xy(combined_nearby_df, 'Hex_X', 'Hex_Y')

scatter_plot_nearby_results(combined_nearby_sdf, 'Nearby transit stops for 75% percentile', 'Nearby transit stop count (From Spatial Analysis on static GTFS stop data)', 'Rounded Trip Count (Scooter data)')

def calculate_distance_column(sdf, centroid_point):
    sdf = arcgis.features.GeoAccessor.from_xy(sdf, 'Hex_X', 'Hex_Y')
    return sdf['SHAPE'].apply(lambda s: s.distance_to(centroid_point))

Scooter trip data isn't uniformly decreasing¶

What could explain anomalies in the distance to center / scooter trip count relationship?¶

Idea: Population Density¶

Meausred by congestion¶

Use LIVE GTFS data for bus and rail delay times at the intersections from the scooter data

Real-time GTFS vehicle feeds (Trimet - Developer AppID required)¶

import requests, json
appid = 'copy and paste your app id here'
vehicle_url = 'https://developer.trimet.org/ws/v2/vehicles'
r = requests.get(f'{vehicle_url}?appID={appid}')
with open ('gtfs_current_vehicle_locs.json', 'w') as f:
    json.dump(r.json(), f)

Adding socio-economic data to our analysis¶

  • Open Data PDX: https://gis-pdx.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/vulnerability

  • ArcGIS Hub: https://hub.arcgis.com/search?collection=Dataset

We just need a spatial column ...¶

pdx_districts = vulnerable_sdf[['OBJECTID', 'SHAPE']]

filters = {}
for _, row in pdx_districts.iterrows():
    polygon = arcgis.geometry.Polygon(dict(rings=row['SHAPE']['rings'], wkid='4326'))
    sr = arcgis.geometry.SpatialReference('4326')
    _filter = arcgis.geometry.filters.within(polygon, sr)
    filters[row['OBJECTID']] = _filter

data = {}
for object_id, _filter in filters.items():
    _layer = combined_nearby_layer.layers[0].query(filters=_filter)
    # import our data here
